Project: Investigate a TMDb Movie Dataset¶

The project aim to go through a basic process of data analysis with some python libraries including pandas, numpy, matplotlib to provide some interesting insight from the given dataset.

Table of Contents¶

The process include 4 main stages:

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue

Dataset characteristic:

  • 10866 rows and 21 columns
  • Contain some null values and bias informations
  • Rich in aspects available for observation, from financial to audience's taste to production information

The analysis should answer the following main questions:

  1. What are the top movies with highest/lowest revenue/budget/popularity/profit of all time?
  2. What is the movie industry's profit overtime in total and across genres?
  3. What time of the year should the movie be realsed to optimize profit?

Data Cleaning¶

Looking at the sample, there are some columns that provide unnecessary information for analysis such as imdb_id, homepage, tagline... (these column provide extra information about the movie content or a substitute identity for the movie, but the only things we need when refer to the movie should be its offical name)

Also, since budget_adj and revenue_adj would be more appropriate to measure, budget and revenue will be removed

As the analysis will be focus more into the movies, information about actor and production will be eliminated

So i will remove the above columns in the dataset

In [19]:
#create a function to show a bar chart of top movies by sort attribute
def plot_top10_movies(df, x_column, sort_attribute):
    # sort the dataframe by x_column and select the top 10 rows by attribute
    if  sort_attribute == 'highest':
        df_sorted = df.sort_values(x_column, ascending=False).head(10)
    elif sort_attribute == 'lowest':
        df_sorted = df.sort_values(x_column, ascending=True).head(10)
    
    # define the dictionary that maps the column name to the correct name for axis
    column_dic = {"popularity": 'Popularity', "budget_adj": 'Budget (in USD)',
                  "revenue_adj": 'Revenue (in USD)', "profit": 'Profit (in USD)'}
    axis_name=column_dic.get(x_column)       
    
    # create a bar chart 
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    ax = sns.barplot(x="original_title", y=x_column, data=df_sorted, palette="husl")


    # Set the x-axis label and title
    ax.set_xlabel('Movie Name',fontsize = 13)
    ax.set_title(f'Top 10 Movies with {sort_attribute} {axis_name}',fontsize = 15)

    # Set the y-axis label and format
    ax.set_ylabel(f'{axis_name}',fontsize = 13)
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter('${x:,.0f}')

    # display the chart
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.show()

The movie industry's profit accross genres¶

In [25]:
# Get list of genres
genre_list = df_movie['genres'].str.split('|', expand=True)
genre_list = genre_list.apply(pd.Series.value_counts).index.tolist()
genre_list = np.array(genre_list)

#create a dataframe to stores the profit of each genres
df_genre = pd.DataFrame(columns=['genre','profit'])

# Add the NumPy array as a new column in the DataFrame
df_genre['genre'] = genre_list

#Find the profit of each genre:
for i in genre_list:
    df = df_movie[df_movie['genres'].str.contains(i)]

    # Calculate the total profit for the filtered DataFrame   
    df_genre.loc[df_genre['genre'] == i, 'profit'] = df['profit'].mean()


# create a bar chart 
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
ax = sns.barplot(x="genre", y="profit", data=df_genre, palette="husl")


# Set the x-axis label and title
ax.set_xlabel('Genres',fontsize = 13)
ax.set_title('Movie Profit by genres',fontsize = 14)

# Set the y-axis label and format
ax.set_ylabel('Profit (in USD)',fontsize = 13)
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter('${x:,.0f}')

# display the chart
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

It seems like movies in the genres of animation are more likely to make the the most profit. While movies in the Foreign genre bring a negative value

Watching the profit trend of each genre over year¶

I wanted to see how the profit of each genres vary over the year and see if it would be true that making animation movie is less risky now than in the past

In order to do this, it would require me to get the profit of each trend every year and it would be a little more complicated.

In [27]:
# Get list of years and sort from oldest to newest
year_list = df['release_year'].value_counts().index.tolist()
year_list.sort()
year_list = np.array(year_list)

# Create the dataframe with a 'Year' column and genres as column
df_genre_yearly = pd.DataFrame(columns=genre_list)
df_genre_yearly.insert(0, 'Year',value=None)

# Add the NumPy array as a new column in the DataFrame
df_genre_yearly['Year'] = year_list
df_genre_yearly.head()

# Fill in the profit of each years across genres
for i in genre_list:
    for x in year_list:
    #find the profit of the genre 'i' in year 'x'
        df = df_movie[(df_movie['genres'].str.contains(i)) & (df_movie['release_year'] == x)]
  
    #replace the value of the cell in Dataframe
        df_genre_yearly.loc[df_genre_yearly['Year'] == x, i] = df['profit'].mean()

It seems like there is no genre that dominates the average profit alltime, they all experience up and down periods. However, we can assump that the trend is being more and more accurate in the recent times since that the amount of movies produced increase every years, providing more data and make the prediction more accurate.

The animation genre's average profit had a increrible value in 1960s and a spike in 1990s and was among the tops in recent year, this explained why it has the highest average profit of alltime.

Other than animation, some other genres that is stable and have a relative high average profit, espeacially in recent times are adventure, action and fantasy. This can be explained by the assumption that these genres are suitable for audience of all age and guarantee a certain sales. So most of them should have relative stable profit, and if there are loss occured, it wont be large (1)

The Western genre has the most fluctuation and often went negative. Thus being a high risk high return type of movie to produce. An assumption that it is hard to make a good Western, some movies of this genre have a huge loss but sometime an outstanding Western moving would bring enourmous profit and just increase the average value of the genre. (2)

Conclusions¶

The data contains a lot of information and many insights may be pointed of from it. However, im only interest in the financial aspect the movie industry. 

So in my analysis, i first explore some of the movie with highest and lowest revenue/budgest/profit of all time with the adjusted inflation value. 

Secondly, i tried to find out what movie genre dominate the market in term of profit and what genre are likely to make profit. My findings is that animation is the genre that make the most average profits. However, the trend for such value vary based on time period (might be a result of changed in audience's taste). And after visualize the trend overtime, i found that animation, adventure, action, fantasy are the genre that are likely to make the most average profit, while Western movie is a high risk high return genre, which can cause enourmous loss on failure.

Finally, i want to see if the seasonal factors of released date affect the movie's profit and found strong evidence that the movie is likely to make the most profit in the middle of the year or at the end of the year

Limitations of the investigations:¶

  • The above analysis rely only visualization of the dataset. Therefore some conclusions maybe bias and further actions shouldn't be conducted from that. This should be support by statistical tests to see the correlations clearly between the variables
  • Also since the taste and infrastructure for watching movie had changes dramatically over times, the analysis should be more accurate to assets them by dividing time variable to different group ( for ie. pre 2000s and post2000s) this would also help our visualization to be observe easier
